|source=<ref>http://www.colorplanpapers.com/50colours</ref>
}}
'''Marrs green''' is a shade of green that in 2017 won 'The World's Favourite Colour', a major global survey by British paper maker G . F Smith.<ref name=TheCourier>{{cite web|title=The Courier 'Picking the world’s favourite colour|url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/lifestyle/design/466621/picking-worlds-favourite-colour/|website=The Courier}}</ref><ref name=TribuneIndia>{{cite web|title=Tribune India 'Deep teal, world's favourite colour|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/spectrum/arts/deep-teal-world-s-favourite-colour/432660.html|website=Tribune India}}</ref><ref name=MentalFloss>{{cite web|title=Mental Floss 'Marrs Green Named World’s Favorite Color'|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/502509/marrs-green-named-world%E2%80%99s-favorite-color|website=Mental Floss}}</ref>  It is a rich [[teal]] hue.  The color was submitted by Annie Marrs, a [[UNESCO]] worker from [[Dundee]], who was inspired by the [[River Tay]].  The survey received 30,000 submissions from over 100 countries via online polling since it launched in January 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/29/results-worlds-favourite-colour-revealed-green-blue/|title=The results are in: world's favourite colour revealed - but is it green or blue?|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nigeriatoday.ng/2017/07/introducing-marrs-green-the-worlds-favourite-colour-video/|title=Introducing Marrs Green, The World’s Favourite Colour [Video] — Nigeria Today|date=18 July 2017|publisher=}}</ref>

