A '''re-recording''' is a recording produced following a new performance of a work of music. This is most commonly, but not exclusively, by a popular artist or group. It differs from a [[reissue]], which involves a second or subsequent release of a previously-recorded piece of music.
Re-recordings are often produced decades after the original recordings were released, usually under contract terms more favorable to the artists. This is especially common among acts that originally agreed to [[Recording contract|contracts]] that would be considered unfair and exploitative today.<ref name=Slate>{{cite web| url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/culturebox/2013/05/re_recordings_runaway_and_other_classic_songs_redone_in_the_studio_can_we.html| last=Mandl| first=Dave| title=Same old song? Not exactly| date=May 10, 2013|website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]| publisher=The Slate Group LLC| accessdate=September 16, 2015}}</ref> When re-recordings are issued under newer contracts, artists can collect far higher royalties for use in films, commercials, and movie trailers.<ref name=Slate /> Other acts re-record their work for artistic reasons. [[Jeff Lynne]] of the [[Electric Light Orchestra]] released [[Mr. Blue Sky: The Very Best of Electric Light Orchestra|a solo best-of album]] with new versions of previous hits like "[[Mr. Blue Sky]]", the original of which Lynne described as "[not] quite how I meant it".<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/oct/20/artists-rerecording-old-hits |date=October 19, 2012 |last=Pattison | first=Louis |title=From Patrick Wolf to Def Leppard, why do artists keep re-recording their old hits? |newspaper=The Guardian | accessdate=September 16, 2015}}</ref> Re-recordings commonly appear in [[online music store]]s and [[streaming media|streaming]] services, such as the [[iTunes Store]] and [[Spotify]];<ref name=Slate /> the original recording may or may not be available.
